er of perspectives. Topics covered include patients' views on programs for the mentally ill, the needs of families coming to terms with the mental illness of a family member, 'the forgotten sibling,' the concept of grief, the confusion that a family member can experience when dealing simultaneously with the mental health and the criminal justice systems, and the effect of parental mental illness on young children.This volume will be of particular interest to social workers, clinical psychiatrists, psychologists, and other mental health professionals who work primarily with individuals and families who have been affected by major mental illness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aMEDICAL / Mental Health.2bisacsh1 aAbosh, Beverley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBachrach, Leona L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarankin, Tatyana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartha, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButterill, Dale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, April, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, April, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDenberg, Dave, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoncalves, Luis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenberg, Myrna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHatfield, Agnes B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacrae, Debra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaterson, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwirsky, Marlene, econtributor